\begin_layout Standard
1.
 In Homework 1, it was shown that 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathbb{R}\cup\{\infty\},\mathcal{T})$
\end_inset

 was a semialgebra, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{T}$
\end_inset

 consisted of all subintervals of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}\cup\{\infty\}$
\end_inset

 of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $(a,b]$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $-\infty\leq a\leq b\leq\infty$
\end_inset

.
 If we let 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota\colon\mathbb{Q}\to\mathbb{R}\cup\{\infty\}$
\end_inset

 denote the inclusion map, then we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota^{-1}(\mathcal{T})=\mathcal{S}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{S}$
\end_inset

 denotes the collection of all subintervals of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

 of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $(a,b]\cap\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

.
 It follows easily from 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Proposition~(
\backslash
ref{proppullbacksemialgebra})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{S}$
\end_inset

 is a semialgebra of subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Technically we showed that the inverse image of a 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

-algebra is a 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

-algebra.
 However the same reasoning used in that proof shows that the inverse image
 of a semialgebra is a semialgebra: namely 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{-1}$
\end_inset

 commutes with complements and unions.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Therefore the set of all finite disjoint unions of members of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{S}$
\end_inset

 forms an algebra, and as any finite union of members of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{S}$
\end_inset

 can be expressed as a finite disjoint union of members of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{S}$
\end_inset

 (since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{S}$
\end_inset

 is a semialgebra), we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{A}$
\end_inset

 is an algebra.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
2.
 Clearly 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}(\mathbb{Q})\supseteq\sigma(\mathcal{A})$
\end_inset

.
 Let us prove the reverse inclusion.
 We first observe that 
\begin_inset Formula $\{r\}\in\sigma(\mathcal{A})$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $r\in\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, if 
\begin_inset Formula $r\in\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

, then we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\{r\} & =\bigcap_{n\in\mathbb{N}}(r-1/n,r]\cap\mathbb{Q}\in\sigma(\mathcal{A})
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Now let 
\begin_inset Formula $S\in\mathcal{P}(\mathbb{Q})$
\end_inset

.
 Then since 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is countable, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
S & =\bigcup_{s\in S}\{s\}\in\sigma(\mathcal{A}).
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
3.
 We have 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(\emptyset)=0$
\end_inset

 by definition.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(A_{n})$
\end_inset

 be a sequence of pairwise disjoint members of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{A}$
\end_inset

 whose union also belongs to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{A}$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\bigcup_{n=1}^{\infty}A_{n}\neq\emptyset$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{n}\neq\emptyset$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

, and thus
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mu\left(\bigcup_{n=1}^{\infty}A_{n}\right) & =\infty\\
 & =\mu(A_{n})\\
 & =\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\mu(A_{n}).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Similarly, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\bigcup_{n=1}^{\infty}A_{n}=\emptyset$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{n}=\emptyset$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

, and thus 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mu\left(\bigcup_{n=1}^{\infty}A_{n}\right) & =0\\
 & =\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}0\\
 & =\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\mu(A_{n}).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

In both cases, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mu\left(\bigcup_{n=1}^{\infty}A_{n}\right)=\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\mu(A_{n})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
4.
 We define 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{1}\colon\mathcal{P}(\mathbb{Q})\to[0,\infty]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{2}\colon\mathcal{P}(\mathbb{Q})\to[0,\infty$
\end_inset

] by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mu_{1}(A)=\begin{cases}
|A| & \text{if }A\text{ is finite}\\
\infty & \text{else}
\end{cases}\quad\text{and}\quad\mu_{2}(A)=\begin{cases}
0 & \text{if }A=\emptyset\\
\infty & \text{if }A\neq\emptyset
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $A\in\mathcal{P}(\mathbb{Q})$
\end_inset

.
 Both 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{2}$
\end_inset

 restrict to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 as functions since every member of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{A}$
\end_inset

 is infinite.
 They are also both distinct as functions since, for example, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{1}(\{x\})=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{2}(\{x\})=\infty$
\end_inset

 for any 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus it suffices to show that they are measures.
 That 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{2}$
\end_inset

 is a measure follows from a similar argument as in the case of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

, so we just show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{1}$
\end_inset

 is a measure.
 We have 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{1}(\emptyset)=0$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $|\emptyset|=0$
\end_inset

.
 Next we show it is finitely additive.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 be members of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}(\mathbb{Q})$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $A\cap B=\emptyset$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $A=\emptyset$
\end_inset

, then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mu_{1}(A\cup B) & =\mu_{1}(\emptyset\cup B)\\
 & =\mu_{1}(B)\\
 & =0+\mu_{1}(B)\\
 & =\mu_{1}(\emptyset)+\mu_{1}(B)\\
 & =\mu_{1}(A)+\mu_{1}(B).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Similarly, if 
\begin_inset Formula $B=\emptyset$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{1}(A\cup B)=\mu_{1}(A)\cup\mu_{1}(B)$
\end_inset

.
 So assume neither 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 nor 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 is the emptyset.
 Write them as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A=\{x_{1},\dots x_{m}\}\quad\text{and}\quad B=\{y_{1},\dots,y_{n}\}.
\]

\end_inset

Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A\cup B=\{x_{1},\dots,x_{m},y_{1},\dots,y_{n}\},
\]

\end_inset

and so
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mu_{1}(A\cup B) & =m+n\\
 & =\mu_{1}(A)+\mu_{1}(B).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{1}$
\end_inset

 is finitely additive.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Now, let 
\begin_inset Formula $(A_{n})$
\end_inset

 be a sequence of pairwise disjoint members of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}(\mathbb{Q})$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{n}\neq\emptyset$
\end_inset

 for only finitely many 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, say 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{1},\dots,n_{k}$
\end_inset

.
 Then it follows from finite additivity of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{1}$
\end_inset

 and the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(\emptyset)=0$
\end_inset

 that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mu_{1}\left(\bigcup_{n=1}^{\infty}A_{n}\right) & =\mu_{1}\left(\bigcup_{i=1}^{k}A_{n_{i}}\right)\\
 & =\sum_{i=1}^{k}\mu(A_{n_{i}})\\
 & =\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\mu(A_{n}).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Now suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{n}\ne\emptyset$
\end_inset

 for infinitely many 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 By taking a subsequence of 
\begin_inset Formula $(A_{n})$
\end_inset

 if necessary, we may assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{n}\neq\emptyset$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\bigcup_{n=1}^{\infty}A_{n}$
\end_inset

 is infinite, and so
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mu_{1}\left(\bigcup_{n=1}^{\infty}A_{n}\right) & =\infty\\
 & \geq\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\mu_{1}(A_{n})\\
 & \geq\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}1\\
 & =\infty.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mu_{1}\left(\bigcup_{n=1}^{\infty}A_{n}\right)=\infty=\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\mu_{1}(A_{n}).
\]

\end_inset

Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{2}$
\end_inset

 are distinct measures which restrict to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

